{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 16:20:58,517", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_validation_result", "line": 185, "message": "{\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-26T16:20:58.517860\", \"task_id\": \"unknown\", \"task_objective\": \"Implement an evaluation engine that scores candidate answers on relevance, depth, confidence, and technical accuracy across categories.\", \"result\": \"```python\\nclass EvaluationEngine:\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    A class to evaluate candidate answers based on relevance, depth,\\n    confidence, and technical accuracy across different categories.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n\\n    def __init__(self, weight_relevance=0.25, weight_depth=0.25,\\n                 weight_confidence=0.25, weight_accuracy=0.25):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Initializes the EvaluationEngine with weights for each evaluation criterion.\\n\\n        Args:\\n            weight_relevance (float): Weight for relevance score.\\n     ...\", \"validation_type\": \"text\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"feedback\": \"here are some feedbacks:\\n1. The placeholder methods need concrete implementations to actually score answers rather than always returning fixed levels.\\n2. Use simple NLP/text‐processing techniques (difflib for similarity, keyword overlap for accuracy, hedging-word detection for confidence).\\n3. Define clear thresholds for converting numeric metrics into “High”, “Medium”, “Low” levels.\\n4. Remove comments about “needs to be implemented” and supply working code.\\n5. Keep the rubric interface unchanged.\\n\\nhere are the changes:\\n```python\\nimport difflib\\nimport re\\n\\nclass EvaluationEngine:\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    A class to evaluate candidate answers based on relevance, depth,\\n    confidence, and technical accuracy across different categories.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n\\n    def __init__(self, weight_relevance=0.25, weight_depth=0.25,\\n                 weight_confidence=0.25, weight_accuracy=0.25):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Initializes the EvaluationEngine with weights for each evaluation criterion.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        self.weight_relevance = weight_relevance\\n        self.weight_depth = weight_depth\\n        self.weight_confidence = weight_confidence\\n        self.weight_accuracy = weight_accuracy\\n        # hedging words often indicate lower confidence\\n        self.hedging_patterns = re.compile(\\n            r'\\\\b(i think|maybe|perhaps|possibly|might|could)\\\\b', re.IGNORECASE)\\n\\n    def evaluate_answer(self, answer, expected_answer, technical_domain,\\n                        relevance_rubric, depth_rubric, confidence_rubric, accuracy_rubric):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Evaluates a candidate's answer based on predefined rubrics.\\n        Returns scores and overall weighted score.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        # Assess each dimension\\n        rel_level = self._assess_relevance(answer, expected_answer)\\n        depth_level = self._assess_depth(answer, expected_answer)\\n        conf_level = self._assess_confidence(answer)\\n        acc_level = self._assess_accuracy(answer, expected_answer)\\n\\n        # Map levels to numeric scores\\n        rel_score = relevance_rubric.get(rel_level, 0)\\n        depth_score = depth_rubric.get(depth_level, 0)\\n        conf_score = confidence_rubric.get(conf_level, 0)\\n        acc_score = accuracy_rubric.get(acc_level, 0)\\n\\n        overall_score = (\\n            self.weight_relevance * rel_score +\\n            self.weight_depth * depth_score +\\n            self.weight_confidence * conf_score +\\n            self.weight_accuracy * acc_score\\n        )\\n\\n        return {\\n            'relevance_score': rel_score,\\n            'depth_score': depth_score,\\n            'confidence_score': conf_score,\\n            'accuracy_score': acc_score,\\n            'overall_score': round(overall_score, 2)\\n        }\\n\\n    def _assess_relevance(self, answer, expected):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Uses sequence similarity to judge how closely the answer matches expected.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        if not answer or not expected:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n        ratio = difflib.SequenceMatcher(None, answer.lower(), expected.lower()).ratio()\\n        if ratio >= 0.8:\\n            return \\\"High\\\"\\n        elif ratio >= 0.5:\\n            return \\\"Medium\\\"\\n        else:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n\\n    def _assess_depth(self, answer, expected):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Compares answer length to expected answer length as a proxy for depth.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        if not answer:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n        len_ans = len(answer.split())\\n        len_exp = max(len(expected.split()), 1)\\n        ratio = len_ans / len_exp\\n        if ratio >= 1.2:\\n            return \\\"High\\\"\\n        elif ratio >= 0.8:\\n            return \\\"Medium\\\"\\n        else:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n\\n    def _assess_confidence(self, answer):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Detects hedging expressions to infer confidence.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        if not answer:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n        count_hedges = len(self.hedging_patterns.findall(answer))\\n        # fewer hedges → higher confidence\\n        if count_hedges == 0:\\n            return \\\"High\\\"\\n        elif count_hedges <= 2:\\n            return \\\"Medium\\\"\\n        else:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n\\n    def _assess_accuracy(self, answer, expected):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Measures keyword overlap between answer and expected to estimate accuracy.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        if not answer or not expected:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n        # Extract unique alphanumeric tokens\\n        tokenize = lambda text: set(re.findall(r'\\\\b\\\\w+\\\\b', text.lower()))\\n        ans_tokens = tokenize(answer)\\n        exp_tokens = tokenize(expected)\\n        if not exp_tokens:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n        overlap = ans_tokens.intersection(exp_tokens)\\n        ratio = len(overlap) / len(exp_tokens)\\n        if ratio >= 0.8:\\n            return \\\"High\\\"\\n        elif ratio >= 0.5:\\n            return \\\"Medium\\\"\\n        else:\\n            return \\\"Low\\\"\\n\\n\\nif __name__ == '__main__':\\n    # Example Usage:\\n    engine = EvaluationEngine()\\n\\n    # Define rubrics\\n    relevance_rubric = {\\\"High\\\": 10, \\\"Medium\\\": 7, \\\"Low\\\": 3}\\n    depth_rubric = {\\\"High\\\": 10, \\\"Medium\\\": 7, \\\"Low\\\": 3}\\n    confidence_rubric = {\\\"High\\\": 10, \\\"Medium\\\": 7, \\\"Low\\\": 3}\\n    accuracy_rubric = {\\\"High\\\": 10, \\\"Medium\\\": 7, \\\"Low\\\": 3}\\n\\n    # Example question and answer\\n    candidate_answer = \\\"The 'def' keyword in Python is used to define functions and it's very straightforward.\\\"\\n    expected_answer = \\\"The 'def' keyword is used to define functions in Python.\\\"\\n    technical_domain = \\\"Python\\\"\\n\\n    scores = engine.evaluate_answer(\\n        candidate_answer,\\n        expected_answer,\\n        technical_domain,\\n        relevance_rubric,\\n        depth_rubric,\\n        confidence_rubric,\\n        accuracy_rubric\\n    )\\n\\n    print(scores)\\n```\"}"}
